description.plain:
Bill Kahan Kapri (born Dieuson Octave on June 11, 1997), better known as Kodak Black, is a rapper from Pompano Beach, Florida. A rapper since the age of 12, Kodak first began to rise in popularity after Drake posted an Instagram video dancing along to Kodak’s song “SKRT.”.

In an Interview with Passion of the Weiss, Kodak explained that his rap name originated from the nickname “Lil' Black”. When he joined Instagram he chose the username “Kodak Black”, “…‘cause you know Kodak, that’s pictures and all that.” This later became his stage name when he started to rap and a name favored by his fans.

From 2013 to 2015, Kodak had begun to start rapping while releasing two mixtapes in the time period. On December 26, 2013, Yak released his debut mixtape titled Project Baby which grew in popularity from the rise of “Signs”. Following its release, almost a year later, Kodaks sophomore mixtape Heart of the Projects had released while containing one of the artists most notable tracks, “No Flockin.”

In October 2015, Yak was arrested for charges such as robbery, battery, false imprisonment of a child, and possession of cannabis, however, was subsequently released. Kodak then used his arrest to release his jail-themed mixtape, Institution.

2016 to 2017 was a bright, yet extremely inconvenient couple of years for Kodak. Releasing a total of 5 projects. Yak began his 2016 after being arrested in April 2016 in Hallandale Beach, Florida, and charged with possession of a weapon by a convicted felon, possession of marijuana, and fleeing from officers. He later began his musical year with the release of Lil B.I.G. Pac released on June 11, 2016; he earned features from Gucci Mane, PnB Rock, and Boosie Badazz, peaking at #134 on the Billboard 200. After this, he was arrested twice, again, in Florida.

In 2017, Kodak released two mixtapes and his debut album, Painting Pictures which peaked at #3 on the Billboard 200. However, this year was more of a negative, than a positive year for Kodak. He was arrested for violating his probation in February 2017 and was later indicted and set for trial in 2019.  In May 2017, he was yet again arrested for violating his house arrest and sentenced to a year in Broward County Jail. Attaining an early release, on June 5, 2017, it was set that he will remain on house arrest for one year, and five years of probation.

In January 2018, Kodak was arrested for multiple charges. Following his charges, Kodak released his valentines day special mixtape, Heart Break Kodak which peaked at #25 on the Billboard 200. Just over a week later, his January charges were dropped. In April 2018, Kodak plead not guilty to several charges and was sentenced to a year with credit for time served. He was then released in August 2018.

Following his release, his almost chart-topping song, “ZEZE” featuring Offset and Travis Scott, the track peaked at #2 on the Billboard Hot 100  making it his highest-charting song yet. The track was featured on Yak’s December 2018 sophomore album, Dying to Live which peaked at #1 on the Billboard 200.

In November 2019, following an extremely bad leal year for Kodak, being arrested on countless amounts of charges, he was sentenced to four years in prison after pleading guilty to lying on background paperwork while attempting to buy guns. This would highly affect the artist’s career.

Despite being incarcerated, Kodak’s third studio album Bill Israel contains features from highly notable artists such as Gucci Mane, Tory Lanez, Lil Yachty, and more. Taking a massive drop from his previous project, Bill Israel peaked at #42 on the Billboard 200.

In January 2021, Kodak Black was given a presidential pardon by Donald Trump on his last day in office. Kodak received this alongside Lil Wayne while he was serving a 46-month sentence. To celebrate his freedom, he dropped a single titled “Last Day In”.

Prior to his release, Kodak released three projects, one being a youtube exclusive containing old songs; the most notable is his mixtape, Haitian  Boy Kodak. Despite only gaining a little bit of relevance due to his release, Kodak appeared in articles almost every day concerning his beef with his longtime friend, Jackboy. His music bean to gain as much as relevance he had prior to his sentencing as he released “Super Gremlin” on his label mixtape, Sniper Gang Presents: Nightmare Babies.

On January 2022, Kodak was yet again arrested for trespassing, however, charges were later dropped. While building off of many viral moments.

Yak’s fourth studio album, Back For Everything was released on February 25, 2022. The album featured the viral “Super Gremlin” and “Love & War.”

songs.title: Tunnel Vision

description.plain:
In ‘'Tunnel Vision,’‘ Kodak raps about serving jail time, the corrupt prison system, and other issues he’s faced in the past. Metro Boomin and Southside provide the beat.

Before the song’s release, Kodak teased the track via live performances, on his Instagram, and in several videos that received more than 1 million views before the song officially dropped.

The “Tunnel Vision” music video shows Kodak standing in front of a burning cross—a reference to the KKK. The video also features a white man wearing a hat that says “Make America Hate Again", a nod to President Donald Trump’s campaign slogan, “Make America Great Again.” The man in the hat prepares to shoot a black man, but his gun fails, and the two come to blows. Finally, a little girl appears and shouts “Stop!” which brings the video to an end.

songs.title: No Flockin

description.plain:
“No Flockin” finds Kodak Black bragging about the almighty dollar. No matter who, where, when or what, he’ll always have money on his mind.

This song was Kodak’s break-out hit. After receiving a buzz for his previous songs, “SKRT” and “Skrilla,” this was the one that led him to be known nation-wide.

The song was also featured in Episode 2 of Drake’s OVO Sound Radio. Before that, Drake was captured on video dancing to Kodak’s “SKRT,” blowing up his spot. However, in an interview with XXL, Kodak said that he didn’t care too much about the 6 God’s co-sign:

I heard about, but I didn’t know what that did. I just knew that was Drake, so… You trying to show you fuck with me or what? We ain’t never talked on the phone, like he was texting me and shit. I’m direct with it. So, if you’re trying to show me that you fuck with me, call me. Throw me on your album so I can get me some royalties.

songs.title: ZEZE

description.plain:
Kodak Black enlists Offset and Travis Scott for “ZEZE,” a song on which the trio discusses their decadent lifestyles on the song. Produced by Chicago-native d.a. got that dope, this track heavily features steel drum instrumentation.

Following “If I’m Lyin, I’m Flyin” two weeks prior, this is Kodak’s second single since being released from jail in August 2018 and the second single from Dying to Live.

In early September 2018, Kodak posted a now-deleted short clip of him and Travis Scott dancing to the song’s instrumental in the studio. This video became a viral sensation known as the #WaitingChallenge that inspired numerous memes. Kodak later posted another video of just himself dancing to the instrumental.

Kodak performed during the Florida A&M University homecoming festivities on October 5, 2018, and announced the song’s name and release date. One day before the song’s release, Kodak posted the cover art, which revealed that Offset was on the song, which was previously unknown. The song was released as expected on October 12, 2018.

The official music video was released on November 23, 2018. Travis Scott directed the video by himself. The video depicts the three rappers having a problem with the original film director, and hence things are the way they are. It is basically a behind-the-scenes twisted video, showing the three under a green screen and editing their effects.

songs.title: SKRT

description.plain:
“SKRT” is the sound that Kodak Black’s tires make when driving away from a sticky situation.

The song was released in 2014, but the track only started gaining momentum in late 2015, after receiving Drake’s highly coveted cosign—on the sixth episode of OVO Sound Radio and on his Instagram account.

https://instagram.com/p/9NIha_jQGu/?taken-by=champagnepapi

Despite the impact Drizzy had on introducing “SKRT” to the masses, Kodak told The Fader that he’s greater than the cosign: “Drake ain’t make me.”

The New Yorker wrote that “SKRT” is “a primal declaration of forward momentum.”

With this hook, Octave joins other young rappers who have rejected an old-school emphasis on lyrical variety, individualism, and personal catharsis. (Remember how he feels about school?) These are the devices that helped turn Kanye West and Eminem into stars; Octave and peers like Silentó and Desiigner have been castigated by some

songs.title: Codeine Dreaming

description.plain:
“Codeine Dreaming” marks the first collaboration between Kodak Black and Lil Wayne. It first appeared on the deluxe version of Kodak’s 2017 mixtape Project Baby 2 and then on his 2018 mixtape Heart Break Kodak.

The collaboration was a surprise to fans and media since Kodak and Wayne had previously taken shots at each other. In an interview with the New York Times in October 2016, Wayne claimed he didn’t know who Kodak Black even was. Kodak responded by re-tweeting a fans suggestion that he is this generation’s Lil Wayne and challenging Wayne to a boxing match.

The track itself plays around with dreaming and space metaphors. Both refer to highs caused by using codeine and other drugs. Wayne and Kodak also use the latter to wax lyrical about being far beyond their competition. The production also resembles the noises made by a spaceship, creating an ‘out of this world’ atmosphere.

songs.title: Transportin’

description.plain:
Released in 18 August 2017 along with Kodaks album “Project Baby 2”, “Transportin' ” is a song where Kodak shows off his luxurious and unique lifestyle, boasting about his high amount of money, drugs, guns and his fast transportation/supercars.

Even though he mentions lyrics like “Ridin' sporty, actin' sporty, I can’t control it” and “Bought it ‘cause I wanted it” he mixes the criminal theme about his life into this song as well creating a classic yet typical trap song.

The music video to “Transportin' ” is very flashy and conceited as he dances whilst showing off expensive things from multiple vehicles in the specific colour orange to his high amount of cash.

Notably, everything in the music video is a dark cyan colour or orange. By doing this Kodak represents his home state Florida. The football team “Florida Gators” is seen on his clothing and furniture and everything is themed to represent his love for Florida and the football team.

description.plain:
One month before the start of his Dying to Live Tour, Kodak Black keep his fans waiting with a brand new single, “Pimpin' Ain’t Eazy.” The song comes with an accompanying music video.

“Pimpin' Ain’t Eazy” is a classic sentence, as rappers regularly mention it in their lyrics, and is most likely a reference to Big Daddy Kane’s eponymous single; even though the first to ever use it in a song is Ice-T.

This song can be considered as a perfect illustration of egotrip: Kodak is continuously boasting about his success, what seems to pose a move away from Kodak’s introspection through the emotional and more mature rap of his last album Dying to Live.

songs.title: Love & War

description.plain:
“Love and War” by Kodak Black first surfaced as a one minute CDQ snippet that leaked on a SoundCloud post on December 6, 2019. https://soundcloud.com/user-376590146/kodak-black-puff-ft-03-greedo-snippet?utm_source=mobi&utm_campaign=social_sharing

In November of 2021, the song would start to gain traction on TikTok because of the lyrics from the chorus, bringing in over 300,000 videos by the time of the release in late 2021.

The popular piano beat was produced by Pompano Puff and J Gramm, two producers who have both worked with Kodak previously. J-Gramm did not previously have his producer tag on the snippet version.

Kodak’s chorus was used on a Shorline Mafia track named “On the Low” in July 2020. Despite the use of the chorus, in December 2021, Kodak unexpectedly released the track using the same lyrics.

songs.title: Super Gremlin

description.plain:
“Super Gremlin” is one of the more notable songs on the Sniper Gang sophomore compilation record, Sniper Gang Presents: Nightmare Babies. The title of the track represents Kodak’s grimy and scandalous personality.

Throughout the lyrics, Kodak alludes to fellow Sniper Gang rappers and frequent collaborators, Jackboy. Kodak describes how the two could have been superstars, and reminisces on memories saying that somebody switched up.

Using the melody of “Errror,” producers Jambo and ATL Jacob pitch the voice of How To Loot Brazil higher to outline the intro and to guide the chorus; ultimately delivering a relaxed sound, contradicting the gritty lyrics Kodak raps.

Days after the release of the audio, on November 1, 2021, the official music video—directed by Andre Rene—was released. The video starred Kodak and Nepthys the Goddess; the latter wearing a costume and make-up that resembles a gremlin.

On January 11, 2022, after the soaring success the song received, it was re-released for urban contemporary radio use.

The song was later placed on Yak’s fourth studio album, Back For Everything.
